{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f020c3ae-90cc-4d6e-abce-5ee9ae4a4944","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** / .NET 9, so you can use the modern constructor-injection pattern (available since MSTest 3.3+):\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client = null!;\n\n    // Constructor: sync init + TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // synchronous setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async init runs before each test\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitAsync()\n    {\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/warmup\");\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public void Cleanup() => _client?.Dispose();\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor** — use for sync setup and `TestContext` injection (MSTest 3.3+).\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — supports `async Task` for async setup; runs before each test.\n- Avoid the older `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern — constructor injection is now preferred.\n- For **class-level** async init, use `[ClassInitialize]` with an `async Task` signature.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"161a7443-269f-4dc5-9323-3d52f72dd09f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended modern approach uses:\n\n1. **`TestContext`** — injected via a constructor parameter (MSTest 3.3+) or as a property.\n2. **`[TestInitialize]`** for synchronous init (can also be async).\n3. **`[TestInitialize]`** supports `async Task` return type for async initialization.\n\nBut actually, there's a nuance. In MSTest v3:\n- `TestContext` can be injected via constructor (MSTest 3.3+).\n\n\n- `[TestInitialize]` can be sync or async (`Task`-returning).\n- For class-level init, `[ClassInitialize]` works similarly.\n\nSo the modern pattern supports constructor injection of `TestContext`, and `[TestInitialize]` handles both synchronous and asynchronous initialization, letting you combine sync constructor logic with async setup when needed.\n\nThe cleanest approach is using the constructor for synchronous initialization and `TestContext` injection, then delegating async work to an async `[TestInitialize]` method.","outputTokens":730,"requestId":"CFC5:180DF7:609A842:6C1EBA2:69EC1721"},"id":"48734dac-58fe-4eba-8f08-b790f48739c7","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:21:52.864Z","parentId":"6fc86aa0-aad6-4b01-aaa1-15df28f64d2b"}
